# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-society-for-engineering-education
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] Minerick earned a B.S. in chemical engineering from Michigan Technological University.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] She completed a M.S. and Ph.D. in chemical and biomolecular engineering from the University of Notre Dame.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] Her 2003 dissertation was titled, *Medical Diagnostic Microfluidics and Physiological Blood Flow Dynamics*.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] Hsueh-Chia Chang was her doctoral advisor.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] In 2007, Minerick received a National Science Foundation CAREER Award.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] From 2018 to 2021, Minerick served as Dean of the School of Technology and later the School of Computing in the College of Engineering at the Michigan Technological University from 2018 to 2021.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] She is a professor of Chemical Engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] She was president of the American Society for Engineering Education from 2021 to 2022.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/adrienne-minerick] She is a past president of the American Electrophoresis Society and a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science and the American Institute of Chemical Engineers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] The **American Society for Engineering Education** (**ASEE**) is a non-profit member association, founded in 1893, dedicated to promoting and improving engineering and engineering technology education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] The purpose of ASEE is the advancement of education in all of its functions which pertain to engineering and allied branches of science and technology, including the processes of teaching and learning, counseling, research, extension services and public relations.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE administers the engineering technology honor society Tau Alpha Pi.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] A full reading of the history of ASEE can be found in a 1993 centennial article in the Journal of Engineering Education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Founded initially as the **Society for the Promotion of Engineering Education** (SPEE) in 1893, the society was created at a time of great growth in American higher education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] In 1862, Congress passed the Morrill Land-Grant Act, which provided money for states to establish public institutions of higher education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] These institutions focused on providing practical skills, especially "for the benefit of Agriculture and the Mechanic Arts".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] As a result of increasingly available higher education, more Americans started entering the workforce with advanced training in applied fields of knowledge.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] However, they often lacked grounding in the science and engineering principles underlying this practical knowledge.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] After a generation of students had passed through these new public universities, professors of engineering began to question whether they should adopt a more rigorous approach to teaching the fundamentals of their field.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Ultimately, they concluded that engineering curricula should stress fundamental scientific and mathematical principles, not hands-on apprenticeship experiences.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] To organize support for this approach to engineering education, SPEE was formed in the midst of the 1893 Chicago World’s Fair.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Known as the World's Columbian Exposition, this event heralded the promise of science and engineering by introducing many Americans, for example, to the wonders of electricity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Emerging out of the Fair’s World Engineering Congress, SPEE members dedicated themselves to improving engineering education at the classroom level.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Over its history, the society has put out several reports on the subject, such as the Mann Report (1907), the Wickenden Study (1920s), and the Grinter Report (1955).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] From 1929 to 1930, the society's president was Robert I.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Rees, a retired US Army brigadier general and executive with AT&T.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] During World War II, the federal government started to place more emphasis on research, prompting SPEE to form the Engineering College Research Association (ECRA), which was more concerned with research than SPEE had ever been.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] The ECRA spoke for most engineering researchers, sought federal funds, and collected and published information on academic engineering research.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Van Leer was the chairman and oversaw several committees during this process.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] After the war, the desire to integrate the less research-oriented SPEE with the ECRA resulted in the disbanding of SPEE and the formation of ASEE in 1946.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE was a volunteer-run organization through the 1950s.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] In 1961, ASEE established a staff headquarters in Washington, DC, and undertook a more activist posture.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] However, through the 1960s, the Vietnam War and social unrest, in general, made the mood on many campuses anti-technology, anti-business, and anti-establishment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] In the 1960s and 1970s, ASEE presidents Merritt Williams and George Hawkins reorganized ASEE to better represent its members and return its focus to teaching.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] As a result of this new focus, ASEE began to administer several teaching-related government contracts, including NASA's summer faculty fellowships and the Defense Department's Civil Defense Summer Institutes and Fellowships.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE administered over ten government contracts, including the prestigious National Science Foundation's Graduate Research Fellowship Program until 2019.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Another result of the renewed emphasis on teaching was ASEE’s initiative for recruiting minorities and women into engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE created the Black Engineering College Development program which used industry funding to upgrade engineering faculty in traditionally black colleges and to develop public information on these schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE also received several grants in the 1970s to research the status of women and American Indians and develop programs to attract more of these students to enter engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Since then, ASEE has continued to release studies on the subject in its Journal of Engineering Education, and has created divisions specifically devoted to developing programs and research in this area.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] The *Journal of Engineering Education* is a peer-reviewed academic journal published quarterly in partnership with a global community of engineering education societies and associations.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] The journal is a founding member of the International Federation of Engineering Education Societies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] This directory provides profiles of United States and Canadian schools offering undergraduate and graduate engineering, as well as engineering technology programs with the intent of preparing prospective students for their future education in engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE annually recognizes the outstanding accomplishments of engineering and engineering technology educators through the ASEE awards program.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] By their commitment to their profession, desire to further the Society's mission, and participation in civic and community affairs, ASEE award winners exemplify the best in engineering and engineering technology education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE and its members organize a number of conferences, meetings, and workshops, foremost among them the ASEE Annual Conference.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Other events include regional member meetings, professional-interest focused conferences, and K-12 teacher training.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE administers a number of fellowship and research opportunities with funding provided by federal agencies including the Department of Defense (DOD), NASA, and the National Science Foundation (NSF).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] These range from programs that provide summer internships for high school students to research programs for faculty members during the summer or while on sabbatical.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] Programs include undergraduate and graduate research support and postdoctoral research programs for recent PhDs at government and industrial research facilities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/american-society-for-engineering-education] ASEE provides support tasks that include outreach and promotion activities, application processing support, application review activities, and administration of stipend and tuition payments for program participants.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Watford was born on March 26, 1958, in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] (1985) in industrial engineering and operations research from Virginia Tech College of Engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] During her undergraduate studies, she worked for the Consolidation Coal Company as a cooperative education student.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Her dissertation was titled, *Simulation Software for Bulk Material Transportation System's Analysis*.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Watford started her career as an assistant professor of industrial engineering at Clemson University.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] She moved back to Virginia Tech in 1992 and became the founding executive director of its Center for the Enhancement of Engineering Diversity (CEED) and an associate professor of industrial and systems engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] She became the associate dean for equity and engagement and a professor of engineering education in 1997 and 2005 respectively.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] professor of engineering education in 2005.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Watford was the 2004 to 2005 President of the Women in Engineering ProActive Network and has served on the board of directors of the National Association of Multicultural Engineering Program Administrators.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] From 2005 to 2007, she served as a program manager in the division of undergraduate education for the National Science Foundation (NSF), returning from 2013 to 2015 to serve as the program director for broadening participation in the division of engineering education and centers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] In 2010, she was elected as a fellow of the American Society for Engineering Education and she served as its president from 2017 to 2018.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Watford was its first African-American female president.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] As of 2023, Watford is the associate dean for equity and engagement and professor of engineering education in the Virginia Tech College of Engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] She works to broaden participation in engineering through outreach and student support activities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Watford has secured more than $17 million in funding and support for CEED and other student initiatives.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] Her research activities have focused on the recruitment and retention of students in engineering, with a particular emphasis on minoritized students.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/bevlee-watford] In 2023, U.S. president Joe Biden appointed Watford to the National Science Board.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer was born in Mangum, Oklahoma to Maurice Langhorne Van Leer and Mary McKee Tarleton.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] After his father's death in 1897, he grew up in an all-girls Masonic orphanage in Fort Worth, Texas from the age of 4.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] At an early age he decided he wanted to be an engineer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] He graduated with honors from Purdue University in 1915 with a degree in electrical engineering and later an M.S. in mechanical engineering while working at the University of California, Berkeley in 1920.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer also studied at the University of Caen in France and the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] He was awarded two doctorates, one from Washington & Jefferson College and the other from Purdue.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] In 1924, he married Ella Lillian Wall in Berkeley, California.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Army officer and began his career as an engineer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] During World War I, he led engineering teams who built bridges in front of the main infantry to cross rivers and fought in 5 different battles.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] On one occasion his unit held an island for two days against enemy forces and several members of his unit were killed in action.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] From 1932 to 1937, Van Leer was a dean at the University of Florida.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] During the Great Depression alongside educator and civil rights activist Mary McLeod Bethune, he lobbied for federal funding for Florida institutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] In 1937 he became the dean of the School of Engineering at North Carolina State University.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] During his tenure at both universities, numerous departments were established, and the first graduate engineering programs were created.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] While at NC State he advocated for women and encouraged many to pursue engineering degrees.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The first 5 women would enroll in NC State's engineering programs and become the first to graduate in 1941.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] One of his students was Katharine Stinson, co-founder of Society of Women Engineers and the FAA's first female engineer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] While here, he was also initiated as an honorary of the NCSU chapter of Theta Tau Professional Engineering Fraternity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Around 1940, with the permission of Dean Harrelson, Van Leer gave half his time to the North Carolina Office for Defense orders.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] He resigned his post as dean in 1942 to take military leave.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Army officer (attaining the rank of colonel), after which he returned to lead the school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] In 1945 Blake was appointed to the Board of the United States Naval Academy by President Harry S.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Truman and helped expand its curriculum.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] After World War II, Van Leer returned to become the president of Georgia Tech.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] During his tenure the school admitted women for the first time.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] He began allowing women to enroll in night school, and after a failed vote to allow women into Georgia Tech, he tried again and succeeded by split decision.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Wallace was quoted "as saying Van Leer was a fighter who battled to the bitter end for what he believed," a trait he would show very clearly in late 1955.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The first step towards integration was made during support for the 1956 Sugar Bowl game.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] During his time in office Georgia Tech also became the largest engineering school in the South and the third largest in the US and Canada.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer also had a focus on making Atlanta the "MIT of the South." Throughout his career he lobbied major companies like Lockheed Corporation to expand to Atlanta.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] In 1946, Van Leer was appointed as a member to The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization who had a focus to work against racism through influential statements on race.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer might be best known for events centered around the 1956 Sugar Bowl.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Known for giving frequent commencement speeches at the all-Black Morris Brown College, he stood up to Georgia governor Marvin Griffin's demand to bar Bobby Grier from participating in the 1956 Sugar Bowl game between Georgia Tech and Grier's University of Pittsburgh.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Leading up to the game, Griffin sent numerous telegrams to Tech's Board of Regents and the press saying Georgia should not engage in racially integrated events which had Blacks either as participants or in the stands.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The governor also called on the "Tech boys" to be punished.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Coach Bobby Dodd and students left the whole affair up to Van Leer to battle Griffin and the Board of Regents.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer was summoned by the Regents who commended Griffin for his stand on segregation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer stuck to his statement, even receiving a standing ovation in the faculty senate, and the game went on as planned.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Four years after his death in January 1956, an overwhelming majority of the 2,741 students present voted to endorse the integration of qualified applicants, regardless of race.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer advocated women get into engineering later in his career as well.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Today the building that houses Tech's school of Electrical and Computer Engineering bears his name.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer also founded Southern Polytechnic State University while president of Georgia Tech.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The university merged into Kennesaw State University in 2015.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer died of a heart attack on January 24, 1956, at the Atlanta Veterans Hospital.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer was a descendant of the Van Leer Family.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] His direct ancestor Samuel Van Leer was an American Revolutionary War officer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Another ancestor is a Founding Father General Anthony Wayne who is the namesake for Bruce Wayne.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] All of Van Leer's children would graduate as engineers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Peck also became a college president and women's rights advocate after earning her master's degree and Doctorate in engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] After earning a master's degree and multiple engineering degrees, his son Blake Wayne Van Leer also became a high-ranked military officer for the United States Navy.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] His youngest son Samuel Van Leer graduated from Georgia Tech with two engineering degrees, later a masters and led several private schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer is widely credited with laying the groundwork for Georgia Tech's evolution into a major research university and for championing policies of inclusion during a pivotal time in the American South.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The building that houses Georgia Tech's school of Electrical and Computer Engineering bears his name.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Van Leer Scholarship was named after him, it's for out of state students attending Georgia Tech.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] The Van Leer society at NC State University is named after him.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] Artist Julian Hoke Harris sculpted a plaque to honor his stance against Governor Griffin.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/blake-r-van-leer] In 2022 a film was announced about the 1956 Sugar Bowl and it featuring him as a main character.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Luks received a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering from Texas A&M University.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] She completed a master's degree in applied mathematics and a Ph.D. in chemical engineering from the University of Tulsa.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Her 1993 dissertation was titled, *Solute Separabilities in Solvent Gas-Rich Liquid-Liquid-Vapor Systems Topographical and Molecular Consideration*.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Luks began her academic career at the University of Tulsa, where she spent over twenty years teaching and contributing to the chemical engineering field.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] During her tenure, she made the uncommon choice to focus on teaching rather than the more traditional research-intensive career path.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] This decision was considered unconventional at the time, but she embraced it as an opportunity to concentrate on her strengths in teaching and mentoring students.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] In 2014, Luks joined the faculty at Missouri University of Science and Technology (S&T) as an associate teaching professor in the departments of chemical and biochemical engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] She advanced to the rank of teaching professor in 2019.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Her work at S&T also includes serving as the associate chair of the Linda and Bipin Doshi Department of Chemical and Biochemical Engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Luks has been actively involved with the American Society for Engineering Education (ASEE) since attending its conference in Rolla, Missouri, in 1998.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Over the years, she has chaired and presented at numerous ASEE events and has been recognized for her efforts with several awards.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] She held leadership roles within the organization, including vice president for professional interest councils from 2021 to 2022 and vice president for member affairs, a position she held as of 2024.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] In March 2024, Luks was elected president-elect of ASEE.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] She will officially began her term following the organization's annual conference in Portland, Oregon, in June 2024, and will assume the role of president after the 2025 ASEE annual conference in Montreal.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] Luks will be the first teaching-focused, non-tenured professor to lead the organization.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/christi-luks] In addition to her involvement with ASEE, Luks was elected a fellow of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers in 2020 and serves as the president of Omega Chi Epsilon.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/don-giddens] In 1996, he received the Robert Henry Thurston Lecture Award from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/don-giddens] In 1999, Giddens was elected as a member into the National Academy of Engineering for contributions to the understanding of the ultrasound and fluid mechanics of arteriosclerosis, and enhancing academic bioengineering education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/don-giddens] He was the president of the American Society for Engineering Education for the 2011–2012 term.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The precise definition of education is disputed, and there are disagreements about what the aims of education are and to what extent education is different from indoctrination by fostering critical thinking.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] These disagreements affect how to identify, measure, and improve forms of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Fundamentally, education socializes children into society by teaching cultural values and norms.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It equips them with the skills needed to become productive members of society.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This way, it stimulates economic growth and raises awareness of local and global problems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Organized institutions affect many aspects of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For example, governments set education policies to determine when school classes happen, what is taught, and who can or must attend.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] International organizations, like UNESCO, have been influential in promoting primary education for all children.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many factors influence whether education is successful.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Psychological factors include motivation, intelligence, and personality.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Social factors, like socioeconomic status, ethnicity, and gender, are often linked to discrimination.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further factors include access to educational technology, teacher quality, and parent involvement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The main academic field investigating education is called education studies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It examines what education is, what aims and effects it has, and how to improve it.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education studies has many subfields, like philosophy, psychology, sociology, anthropology, and economics of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It also discusses comparative education, pedagogy, and the history of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In prehistory, education happened informally through oral communication and imitation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] With the rise of ancient civilizations, writing was invented, and the amount of knowledge grew.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This caused a shift from informal to formal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Initially, formal education was mainly available to elites and religious groups.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The invention of the printing press in the 15th century made books more widely available.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Beginning in the 18th and 19th centuries, public education became more important.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This development led to the worldwide process of making primary education available to all, free of charge, and compulsory up to a certain age.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Today, over 90% of all primary-school-age children worldwide attend primary school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The term "education" is derived from the Latin words *educare*, meaning "to bring up" and *educere*, meaning "to bring forth".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The definition of education has been explored by theorists from various fields.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many agree that education is a purposeful activity aimed at achieving goals like the transmission of knowledge, skills, and character traits.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Extensive debate surrounds its exact nature beyond these general features.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] One approach views education as a process that occurs during events such as schooling, teaching, and learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Another outlook understands education not as a process but as the mental states and dispositions of educated persons that result from this process.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Additionally, the term may also refer to the academic field that studies the methods, processes, and social institutions involved in teaching and learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Having a clear idea of what the term means matters when trying to identify educational phenomena, measure educational success, and improve educational practices.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some theorists provide precise definitions by identifying the specific features that are exclusive to all forms of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Peters, for instance, outlines three essential features of education, which include that knowledge and understanding are imparted to the student and that this process is beneficial and done in a morally appropriate manner.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Such precise definitions often succeed at characterizing the most typical forms of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] However, they often face criticism because less common types of education occasionally fall outside their parameters.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The difficulty of dealing with counterexamples not covered by precise definitions can be avoided by offering less exact definitions based on family resemblance instead.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This means that all forms of education are similar to one another, but they need not share a set of essential features.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some education theorists, such as Keira Sewell and Stephen Newman, hold that the term "education" is context-dependent.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Evaluative or thick conceptions of education state that it is part of the nature of education to lead to some kind of improvement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They contrast with thin conceptions, which provide a value-neutral explanation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some theorists provide a descriptive conception of education by observing how the term is commonly used in ordinary language.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Prescriptive conceptions, by contrast, define what good education is or how education should be practiced.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many thick and prescriptive conceptions see education as an activity that tries to achieve certain aims, which may range from acquiring knowledge and learning to think rationally to nurturing character traits like kindness and honesty.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Various scholars stress the role of critical thinking to distinguish education from indoctrination.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They state that mere indoctrination is only interested in instilling beliefs in the student, independent of whether the beliefs are rational; whereas education also fosters the rational ability to critically reflect on and question those beliefs.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It is not universally accepted that these two phenomena can be clearly distinguished since some forms of indoctrination may be necessary in the early stages of education while the child's mind is not yet sufficiently developed.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This applies to cases in which young children need to learn something without being able to understand the underlying reasons, like certain safety rules and hygiene practices.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education can be characterized from the teacher's or the student's perspective.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Teacher-centered definitions focus on the perspective and role of the teacher in the transmission of knowledge and skills in a morally appropriate way.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Student-centered definitions analyze education from the student's involvement in the learning process and hold that this process transforms and enriches their subsequent experiences.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Definitions taking both perspectives into account are also possible.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This can take the form of describing education as a process of a shared experience of discovering a common world and solving problems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] There are many classifications of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] One of them depends on the institutional framework and distinguishes between formal, non-formal, and informal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Another classification includes distinct levels of education based on factors like the student's age and the complexity of the content.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further categories focus on the topic, teaching method, medium used, and funding.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Tutoring is an example of non-formal education, while learning to cook from one's parents is an example of informal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The most common division is between formal, non-formal, and informal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Formal education happens in a complex institutional framework.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Such frameworks have a chronological and hierarchical order: the modern schooling system has classes based on the student's age and progress, extending from primary school to university.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Formal education is usually controlled and guided by the government.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It tends to be compulsory up to a certain age.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Non-formal and informal education take place outside the formal schooling system.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Non-formal education is a middle ground.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Like formal education, it is organized, systematic, and carried out with a clear purpose, as in the case of tutoring, fitness classes, and the scouting movement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Informal education happens in an unsystematic way through daily experiences and exposure to the environment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Unlike formal and non-formal education, there is usually no designated authority figure responsible for teaching.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Informal education takes place in many different settings and situations throughout one's life, usually in a spontaneous way.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This is how children learn their first language from their parents and how people learn to prepare a dish by cooking together.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some theorists distinguish the three types based on the location of learning: formal education takes place in school, non-formal education happens in places that are not regularly visited, like museums, and informal education occurs in places of everyday routines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] There are also differences in the source of motivation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Formal education tends to be driven by extrinsic motivation for external rewards.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In non-formal and informal education, enjoyment of the learning process usually provides intrinsic motivation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The distinction between the three types is normally clear, but some forms of education do not easily fall into one category.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In primitive cultures, most education occurred informally, and there was little distinction between educational activities and other activities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Instead, the whole environment acted as a form of school, and most adults acted as teachers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Informal education is often not efficient enough to teach large quantities of knowledge.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] To do so, a formal setting and well-trained teachers are usually required.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This was one of the reasons why formal education became increasingly important throughout history.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In this process, the experience of education and the discussed topics became more abstract and removed from daily life while more emphasis was put on grasping general patterns and concepts instead of observing and imitating particular forms of behavior.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Types of education are often divided into levels or stages.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The most influential framework is the International Standard Classification of Education, maintained by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It covers both formal and non-formal education and distinguishes levels based on the student's age, the duration of learning, and the complexity of the discussed content.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further criteria include entry requirements, teacher qualifications, and the intended outcome of successful completion.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The levels are grouped into early childhood education (level 0), primary education (level 1), secondary education (levels 2–3), post-secondary non-tertiary education (level 4), and tertiary education (levels 5–8).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Early childhood education, also known as preschool education or nursery education, begins with birth and lasts until the start of primary school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It follows the holistic aim of fostering early childhood development across the physical, mental, and social domains.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It plays a key role in socialization and personality development and includes various basic skills in the areas of communication, learning, and problem-solving.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This way, it aims to prepare children for their entry into primary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Preschool education is usually optional, but in some countries, such as Brazil, it is mandatory starting from the age of four.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Primary (or elementary) education usually starts between the ages of five and seven and lasts for four to seven years.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It has no further entry requirements, and its main goal is to teach basic skills in reading, writing, and mathematics.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It also covers core knowledge in other fields, such as history, geography, the sciences, music, and art.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A further aim is to foster personal development.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Today, primary education is compulsory in almost all countries, and over 90% of all primary-school-age children worldwide attend primary school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Secondary education follows primary education and usually covers the ages of 12 to 18 years.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It is commonly divided into lower secondary education (middle school or junior high school) and upper secondary education (high school, senior high school, or college depending on the country).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Lower secondary education normally has the completion of primary school as its entry requirement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It aims to extend and deepen learning outcomes, is more focused on subject-specific curricula, and has teachers who specialize in only one or a few subjects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] One of its aims is to familiarize students with the basic theoretical concepts in the different subjects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This helps create a solid basis for lifelong learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In some cases, it also includes basic forms of vocational training.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Lower secondary education is compulsory in many countries in Central and East Asia, Europe, and America.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In some countries, it is the last stage of compulsory education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Mandatory lower secondary education is not as prevalent in Arab states, sub-Saharan Africa, and South and West Asia.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Upper secondary education starts roughly at the age of 15 and aims to provide students with the skills and knowledge needed for employment or tertiary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Its requirement is usually the completion of lower secondary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Its subjects are more varied and complex and students can often choose between a few subjects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Its successful completion is commonly tied to a formal qualification in the form of a high school diploma.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some types of education after secondary education do not belong to tertiary education and are categorized as post-secondary non-tertiary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They are similar in complexity to secondary education but tend to focus more on vocational training to prepare students for the job market.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In some countries, tertiary education is used as a synonym of higher education, while in others, tertiary education is the wider term.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Tertiary education expands upon the foundations of secondary education but has a more narrow and in-depth focus on a specific field or subject.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Its completion leads to an academic degree.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It can be divided into four levels: short-cycle tertiary, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral level education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] These levels often form a hierarchical structure with later levels depending on the completion of previous levels.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Short-cycle tertiary education focuses on practical matters.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It includes advanced vocational and professional training to prepare students for the job market in specialized professions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Bachelor's level education, also referred to as undergraduate education, tends to be longer than short-cycle tertiary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Universities usually offer it as an intermediate academic certification, namely a bachelor's degree.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Master's level education is more specialized than undergraduate education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many programs require independent research in the form of a master's thesis for successful completion.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Doctoral level education leads to an advanced research qualification, normally in the form of a doctor's degree, such as a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It usually requires the submission of a substantial academic work, such as a dissertation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] More advanced levels include post-doctoral studies and habilitation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Successful participation in formal education usually results in a form of certification that is required for higher levels of education and certain professions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Undetected cheating in exams, for example, by using a cheat sheet, threatens to undermine this system if unqualified students are certified.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In most countries, primary and secondary education are free of charge.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] There are significant global differences in the cost of tertiary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A few countries, like Sweden, Finland, Poland, and Mexico, offer tertiary education for free or at a low cost.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In some countries, like the United States and Singapore, tertiary school tuition fees are high and students often have to take substantial loans to afford their studies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] High costs of education can constitute a significant barrier to students in developing countries whose families may be unable to afford school fees, uniforms, and textbooks.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The academic literature discusses many other types of education and distinguishes between traditional and alternative education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Traditional education concerns long-established and mainstream schooling practices.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It uses teacher-centered education and takes place in a well-regulated school environment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Regulations cover many aspects of education, such as the curriculum and the timeframe when classes start and end.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Alternative education is an umbrella term for forms of schooling that differ from the mainstream traditional approach.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Differences may include learning environment, subjects, or the teacher-student relationship.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Alternative schooling is characterized by voluntary participation, relatively small class and school sizes, and personalized instruction.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This often results in a more welcoming and emotionally safe atmosphere.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Alternative education encompasses many types like charter schools and special programs for problematic or gifted children.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It also includes homeschooling and unschooling.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] There are many alternative schooling traditions, like Montessori schools, Waldorf schools, Round Square schools, Escuela Nueva schools, free schools, and democratic schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Alternative education also includes indigenous education, which focuses on the transmission of knowledge and skills from an indigenous heritage and employs methods like narration and storytelling.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further types of alternative schools include gurukul schools in India, madrasa schools in the Middle East, and yeshivas in Jewish tradition.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some distinctions focus on who receives education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Categories by the age of the learner are childhood education, adolescent education, adult education, and elderly education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Categories by biological sex of the students include single-sex education and mixed-sex education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Special education is education that is specifically adapted to meet the unique needs of students with disabilities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It covers various forms of impairments on the intellectual, social, communicative, and physical levels.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It aims to overcome the challenges posed by these impairments.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This way, it provides the affected students with access to an appropriate educational structure.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] When understood in the broadest sense, special education also includes education for very gifted children who need adjusted curricula to reach their fullest potential.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Classifications based on the teaching method include teacher-centered education, in which the teacher takes center stage in providing students with information, and student-centered education, in which students take on a more active and responsible role in shaping classroom activities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For conscious education, learning and teaching happen with a clear purpose in mind.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Unconscious education occurs on its own without being consciously planned or guided.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This may happen in part through the personality of teachers and adults, which can have indirect effects on the development of the student's personality.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Evidence-based education uses scientific studies to determine which methods of education work best.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Its goal is to maximize the effectiveness of educational practices and policies by ensuring that they are informed by the best available empirical evidence.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It includes evidence-based teaching, evidence-based learning, and school effectiveness research.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Autodidacticism, or self-education, happens without the guidance of teachers and institutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It mainly occurs in adult education and is characterized by the freedom to choose what to study and when, which can make it a more fulfilling learning experience.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The lack of structure and guidance can result in aimless learning, and the absence of external feedback may lead autodidacts to develop false ideas and inaccurately assess their learning progress.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Autodidacticism is closely related to lifelong education, which is an ongoing learning process throughout a person's entire life.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Categories of education based on the subject include science education, language education, art education, religious education, physical education, and sex education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Special mediums, such as radio or websites, are used in distance education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Examples include e-learning (use of computers), m-learning (use of mobile devices), and online education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They often take the form of open education, in which courses and materials are made available with minimal barriers to access.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They contrast with regular classroom or on-site education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some forms of online education are not open education, such as full online degree programs offered by some universities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] State education, also referred to as public education, is funded and controlled by the government and available to the general public.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It normally does not require tuition fees and is thus a form of free education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Private education, by contrast, is funded and managed by private institutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Private schools often have a more selective admission process and offer paid education by charging tuition fees.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A more detailed classification focuses on the social institution responsible for education, like family, school, civil society, state, and church.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Compulsory education is education that people are legally required to receive.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It concerns mainly children who need to visit school up to a certain age.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It contrasts with voluntary education, which people pursue by personal choice without a legal requirement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education plays various roles in society, including in social, economic, and personal fields.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] On a social level, education makes it possible to establish and sustain a stable society or can act as a driver of societal transformation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It helps people acquire the basic skills needed to interact with their environment and fulfill their needs and desires.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In modern society, this involves a wide range of skills like being able to speak, read, write, solve arithmetic problems, and handle information and communications technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Socialization also includes learning the dominant social and cultural norms and what kinds of behavior are considered appropriate in different contexts.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education enables the social cohesion, stability, and peace needed for people to productively engage in daily business.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Socialization happens throughout life but is of special relevance to early childhood education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education plays a key role in democracies by increasing civic participation in the form of voting and organizing, and through its tendency to promote equal opportunity for all.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] On an economic level, people become productive members of society through education by acquiring the technical and analytical skills needed to pursue their profession, produce goods, and provide services to others.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In early societies, there was little specialization, and each child would generally learn most of the skills that the community required to function.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Modern societies are increasingly complex and many professions are only mastered by relatively few people who receive specialized training in addition to general education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some of the skills and tendencies learned to function in society may conflict with each other, and their value depends on the context of their usage.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For example, cultivating the tendency to be inquisitive and question established teachings promotes critical thinking and innovation, but in some cases, obedience to an authority is required to ensure social stability.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Median annual salaries across educational levels varied by a factor of about 3.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Median accumulated household wealth across educational levels varied by a factor of over 50.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] By helping people become productive members of society, education stimulates economic growth and reduces poverty.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It helps workers become more skilled and thereby increases the quality of the produced goods and services, which in turn leads to prosperity and increased competitiveness.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Public education is often understood as a long-term investment to benefit society as a whole.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The rate of return is especially high for investments in primary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Besides increasing economic prosperity, it can also lead to technological and scientific advances as well as decrease unemployment while promoting social equity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Increased education is associated with lower birth rates, in part because education augments the awareness of family planning, creates new opportunities for women, and tends to raise the age of marriage.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] However, the rate of return of education can vary due to overqualification.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education can prepare a country to adapt to changes and successfully face new challenges.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It can help raise awareness and contribute to the solution of contemporary global problems, such as climate change, sustainability, and the widening inequalities between the rich and the poor.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] By making students aware of how their lives and actions affect others, it may inspire some to work toward realizing a more sustainable and fair world.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This way, education serves not just the purpose of maintaining the societal status quo, but can also be an instrument of social development.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] That applies also to changing circumstances in the economic sector.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For example, technological advances, particularly increased automation, are accompanied by new demands on the workforce, which education can help address.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Changing circumstances may render currently taught skills and knowledge redundant while shifting the importance to other areas.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education can be used to prepare people for such changes by adjusting the curriculum, introducing subjects like digital literacy, promoting skills in handling new technologies, and including new forms of education such as massive open online courses.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] On a more individual level, education promotes personal development.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This can include factors such as learning new skills, developing talents, fostering creativity, and increasing self-knowledge as well as improving problem-solving and decision-making abilities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education also has positive effects on health and well-being.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The social importance of education is recognized by the annual International Day of Education on January 24.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The United Nations declared the year 1970 the *International Education Year*.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Organized institutions play a key role in various aspects of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Institutions like schools, universities, teacher training institutions, and ministries of education make up the education sector.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They interact both with each other and with other stakeholders, such as parents, local communities, religious groups, non-governmental organizations, professionals in healthcare, law enforcement, media platforms, and political leaders.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many people are directly involved in the education sector, like students, teachers, and school principals as well as school nurses and curriculum developers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Various aspects of formal education are regulated by the policies of governmental institutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] These policies determine at what age children need to attend school and at what times classes are held as well as issues pertaining to the school environment, like infrastructure.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Regulations also cover the exact qualifications and requirements that teachers need to fulfill.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] An important aspect of education policy concerns the curriculum used for teaching at schools, colleges, and universities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A curriculum is a plan of instruction or a program of learning that guides students to achieve their educational goals.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The topics are usually selected based on their importance and depend on the type of school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The goals of public school curricula are usually to offer a comprehensive and well-rounded education, while vocational training focuses more on specific practical skills within a field.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The curricula also cover various aspects besides the topic to be discussed, such as the teaching method, the objectives to be reached, and the standards for assessing progress.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] By determining the curricula, governmental institutions have a strong impact on what knowledge and skills are transmitted to the students.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Examples of governmental institutions include the Ministry of Education in India, the Department of Basic Education in South Africa, and the Secretariat of Public Education in Mexico.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] International organizations also play a key role in education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For instance, UNESCO is an intergovernmental organization that promotes education in many ways.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] One of its activities is to advocate education policies, like the treaty Convention on the Rights of the Child, which states that education is a human right of all children and young people.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The Education for All initiative aimed to offer basic education to all children, adolescents, and adults by the year 2015 and was later replaced by the initiative Sustainable Development Goals as goal 4.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Related policies include the Convention against Discrimination in Education and the Futures of Education initiative.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Some influential organizations are not intergovernmental, but non-governmental.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For example, the International Association of Universities promotes collaboration and the exchange of knowledge between colleges and universities around the world, while the International Baccalaureate offers international diploma programs.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Institutions like the Erasmus Programme facilitate student exchanges between countries, while initiatives such as the Fulbright Program provide a similar service for teachers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Educational success, also called student and academic achievement, refers to the extent to which educational aims are reached, for example, the amount of knowledge and abilities that students acquire.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For practical purposes, it is often measured primarily in terms of official exam scores, but there are many additional indicators, such as attendance rates, graduation rates, dropout rates, student attitudes, and post-school indicators like later income and incarceration rates.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Several factors influence educational achievement, including psychological factors, which concern the student as an individual, and sociological factors, which pertain to the student's social environment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further factors are access to educational technology, teacher quality, and parent involvement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Many of these factors overlap and influence each other.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] On a psychological level, relevant factors include motivation, intelligence, and personality.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Motivation is the internal force propelling people to engage in learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Motivated students are more likely to interact with the content to be learned by participating in classroom activities like discussions, which often results in a deeper understanding of the subject.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Motivation can also help students overcome difficulties and setbacks.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] An important distinction is between intrinsic and extrinsic motivation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Intrinsically motivated students are driven by an interest in the subject and the learning experience itself.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Extrinsically motivated students seek external rewards like good grades and recognition from peers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Intrinsic motivation tends to be more beneficial by leading to increased creativity and engagement as well as long-term commitment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Educational psychologists try to discover how to increase motivation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This can be achieved, for instance, by encouraging some competition among students while ensuring a balance of positive and negative feedback in the form of praise and criticism.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Intelligence influences how people respond to education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It is a mental quality linked to the ability to learn from experience, to understand, and to employ knowledge and skills to solve problems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Those who have higher scores in intelligence metrics tend to perform better at school and go on to higher levels of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Intelligence is often primarily associated with the so-called IQ, a standardized numerical metric for assessing intelligence by focusing on mathematical-logical and verbal skills.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] However, it has been argued that there are more types of intelligence.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] According to the psychologist Howard Gardner, there are distinct forms of intelligence belonging to fields like mathematics, logic, spatial cognition, language, and music.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further types affect how a person interacts with other people and with themselves.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] These types of intelligence are largely independent of each other, meaning that someone may excel at one type while scoring low on another.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] According to proponents of learning style theory, the preferred method of acquiring knowledge and skills is another factor.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They hold that students with an auditory learning style find it easy to comprehend spoken lectures and discussions, whereas visual learners benefit from information presented visually, such as in diagrams and videos.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] To facilitate efficient learning, it may be advantageous to incorporate a wide variety of learning modalities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Learning styles have been criticized for ambiguous empirical evidence of student benefits and unreliability of student learning style assessment by teachers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The learner's personality may also influence educational achievement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For instance, characteristics such as conscientiousness and openness to experience, identified in the Big Five personality traits, are associated with academic success.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Other mental factors include self-efficacy, self-esteem, and metacognitive abilities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Sociological factors focus not on psychological attributes of learners but on their environment and position in society.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They include socioeconomic status, ethnicity, cultural background, and gender.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They are of interest to researchers since they are associated with inequality and discrimination.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For this reason, they play a key role in policy-making in attempts to mitigate their effects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Socioeconomic status depends on income but includes other factors, such as financial security, social status, social class, and quality of life attributes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Low socioeconomic status affects educational success in various ways.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It is linked to slower cognitive developments in language and memory and higher dropout rates.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Poor families may not have enough money to meet basic the nutritional needs of their children, causing poor development.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They may also lack the means to invest in educational resources like stimulating toys, books, and computers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Additionally, they may be unable to afford tuition at prestigious schools and are more likely to attend schools in poorer areas.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Such schools tend to offer lower standards of teaching because of teacher shortages or because they lack educational materials and facilities, like libraries.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Poor parents may also be unable to afford private lessons if their children fall behind.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In some cases, students from an economically disadvantaged background are forced to dropout from school to provide income to their families.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They also have less access to information on higher education and may face additional difficulties in securing and repaying student loans.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Low socioeconomic status also has many indirect negative effects by being linked to lower physical and mental health.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Due to these factors, social inequalities on the level of the parents are often reproduced in the children.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Ethnic background is linked to cultural differences and language barriers, which make it more difficult for students to adapt to the school environment and follow classes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Additional factors are explicit and implicit biases and discrimination toward ethnic minorities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This may affect the students' self-esteem and motivation as well as their access to educational opportunities.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] For example, teachers may hold stereotypical views even if they are not overtly racist, which can lead them to grade comparable performances differently based on the child's ethnicity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Historically, gender has been a central factor in education since the roles of men and women were defined differently in many societies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Education tended to strongly favor men, who were expected to provide for the family.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Women, by contrast, were expected to manage the household and rear children, which barred most educational opportunities available to them.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] While these inequalities have improved in most modern societies, there are still gender differences in education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Among other things, this concerns biases and stereotypes linked to the role of gender in education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They affect subjects like science, technology, engineering, and mathematics, which are often presented as male fields.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This discourages female students from following them.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] One aspect of many social factors is given by the expectations associated with stereotypes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] They work both on an external level, based on how other people react to a person belonging to a certain group, and on an internal level, based on how the person internalizes them and acts accordingly.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In this sense, the expectations may turn into self-fulfilling prophecies by causing the educational outcomes they anticipate.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This can happen both for positive and negative stereotypes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Technology plays another significant role in educational success.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Educational technology is commonly associated with the use of modern digital devices, like computers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] But understood in the broadest sense, it involves a wide range of resources and tools for learning, including basic aids that do not involve the use of machines, like regular books and worksheets.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Educational technology can benefit learning in various ways.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In the form of media, it often takes the role of the primary supplier of information in the classroom.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This means that the teacher can focus their time and energy on other tasks, like planning the lesson and guiding students as well as assessing educational performance.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Educational technology can also make information easier to understand by presenting it using graphics, audio, and video rather than through mere text.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] In this regard, interactive elements may be used to make the learning experience more engaging in the form of educational games.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Technology can be employed to make educational materials accessible to many people, like when using online resources.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It additionally facilitates collaboration between students and communication with teachers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The use of artificial intelligence in education holds various potentials, such as providing new learning experiences to students and assisting teachers in their work, but also poses new risks associated with data privacy, false information, and manipulation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Various organizations promote student access to educational technologies, such as the One Laptop per Child initiative, the African Library Project, and Pratham.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] School infrastructure also influences educational success.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] It includes physical aspects of the school, like its location and size as well as the available school facilities and equipment.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A healthy and safe environment, well-maintained classrooms, and suitable classroom furniture as well as the availability of a library and a canteen tend to contribute to educational success.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] The quality of the teacher also has an important impact on student achievement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Skilled teachers know how to motivate and inspire students and are able to adjust their instructions to the students' abilities and needs.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Important in this regard are the teacher's own education and training as well as their past teaching experience.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] A meta-analysis by Engin Karadağ et al. concludes that, compared to other influences, factors related to the school and the teacher have the biggest impact on educational success.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Parent involvement also boosts achievement and can make children more motivated and invested if they are aware that their parents care about their educational efforts.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] This tends to lead to increased self-esteem, better attendance rates, and more constructive behavior at school.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Parent involvement also includes communication with teachers and other school staff to make other parties aware of current issues and how they may be resolved.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p01] Further relevant factors sometimes discussed in the academic literature include historical, political, demographic, religious, and legal aspects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The main discipline investigating education is called education studies, also referred to as education sciences.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It tries to determine how people transmit and acquire knowledge by studying the methods and forms of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It is interested in its aims, effects, and value as well as the cultural, societal, governmental, and historical contexts that shape education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Education theorists integrate insights from many other fields of inquiry, including philosophy, psychology, sociology, economics, history, politics, and international relations.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Because of these influences, some theorists claim that education studies is not an independent academic discipline like physics or history since its method and subject are not as clearly defined.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Education studies differs from regular training programs, such as teacher training, since its focus on academic analysis and critical reflection goes beyond the skills needed to be a good teacher.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It is not restricted to the topic of formal education but examines all forms and aspects of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Various research methods are used to study educational phenomena.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] They roughly divide into quantitative, qualitative, and mixed-methods approaches.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Quantitative research emulates the methods found in the natural sciences by using precise numerical measurements to gather data from many observations and employs statistical tools to analyze it.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It aims to arrive at an objective and impersonal understanding.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Qualitative research usually has a much smaller sample size and tries to get an in-depth insight into more subjective and personal factors, like how different actors experience the process of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Mixed-methods research aims to combine data gathered from both approaches to arrive at a balanced and comprehensive understanding.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Data can be collected in various ways, like using direct observation or test scores as well as interviews and questionnaires.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Some research projects study basic factors affecting all forms of education, while others concentrate on one specific application, look for solutions to concrete problems, or examine the effectiveness of educational projects and policies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Educational research was found to have low reproducibility.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Education studies encompasses various subfields like pedagogy, comparative education, and the philosophy, psychology, sociology, economics, and history of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The philosophy of education is the branch of applied philosophy that examines many of the basic assumptions underlying the theory and practice of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It studies education both as a process and as a discipline while trying to provide exact definitions of its nature and how it differs from other phenomena.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It further examines the purpose of education, its different types, and how to conceptualize teachers, students, and their relation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It includes educational ethics, which investigates the moral implications of education; for example, what ethical principles direct it and how teachers should apply them to specific cases.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The philosophy of education has a long history and was discussed in ancient Greek philosophy.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The term "pedagogy" is sometimes used as a synonym for education studies, but when understood in a more restricted sense, it refers to the subfield interested in teaching methods.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It studies how the aims of education, like the transmission of knowledge or fostering skills and character traits, can be realized.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It is interested in the methods and practices used for teaching in regular schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Some definitions restrict it to this domain, but in a wider sense, it covers all types of education, including forms of teaching outside schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In this general sense, it explores how teachers can bring about experiences in learners to advance their understanding of the studied topic and how the learning itself takes place.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The psychology of education studies how education happens on the mental level, specifically how new knowledge and skills are acquired as well as how personal growth takes place.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It examines what factors influence educational success, how they may differ between individuals, and to what extent nature or nurture is responsible.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Influential psychological theories of education are behaviorism, cognitivism, and constructivism.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Closely related fields are the neurology of education and educational neuroscience, which are interested in the neuropsychological processes and changes brought about through learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The sociology of education is concerned with how education leads to socialization.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It examines how social factors and ideologies affect what kind of education is available to a person and how successful they are.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Closely related questions include how education affects different groups in society and how educational experiences can form someone's personal identity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The sociology of education is specifically interested in the causes of inequalities, and its insights are relevant to education policy by trying to identify and mitigate factors that cause inequality.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Two influential schools of thought are consensus theory and conflict theory.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Consensus theorists hold that education benefits society as a whole by preparing people for their roles.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Conflict theories have a more negative outlook on the resulting inequalities and see education as a force used by the ruling class to promote their own agenda.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The economics of education is the field of inquiry studying how education is produced, distributed, and consumed.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It tries to determine how resources should be used to improve education, for example, by examining to what extent the quality of teachers is increased by raising their salary.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Other questions are how smaller class sizes affect educational success and how to invest in new educational technologies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This way, the economics of education helps policy-makers decide how to distribute the limited resources most efficiently to benefit society as a whole.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It also tries to understand what long-term role education plays for the economy of a country by providing a highly skilled labor force and increasing its competitiveness.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] A closely related issue concerns the economic advantages and disadvantages of different systems of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Comparative education is the discipline that examines and contrasts systems of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Comparisons can happen from a general perspective or focus on specific factors, like social, political, or economic aspects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Comparative education is often applied to different countries to assess the similarities and differences of their educational institutions and practices as well as to evaluate the consequences of the distinct approaches.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It can be used to learn from other countries which education policies work and how one's own system of education may be improved.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This practice is known as policy borrowing and comes with many difficulties since the success of policies can depend to a large degree on the social and cultural context of students and teachers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] A closely related and controversial topic concerns the question of whether the educational systems of developed countries are superior and should be exported to less developed countries.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Other key topics are the internationalization of education and the role of education in transitioning from an authoritarian regime to a democracy.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The history of education examines the evolution of educational practices, systems, and institutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It discusses various key processes, their possible causes and effects, and their relations to each other.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] A central topic in education studies concerns the question of how people should be educated and what goals should guide this process.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Many aims of education have been suggested, such as the acquisition of knowledge and skills as well as personal development and fostering of character traits.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Common suggestions encompass features like curiosity, creativity, rationality, and critical thinking as well as the tendency to think, feel, and act morally.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Some scholars focus on liberal values linked to freedom, autonomy, and open-mindedness, while others prioritize qualities like obedience to authority, ideological purity, piety, and religious faith.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Some education theorists focus a single overarching purpose of education and see the more specific aims as means to this end.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] On a personal level, this purpose is often identified with helping the student lead a good life.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] On a societal level, education makes people productive members of society.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It is controversial whether the primary aim of education is to benefit the educated person or society as a whole.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Educational ideologies are systems of basic philosophical assumptions and principles that can be used to interpret, understand, and evaluate existing educational practicies and policies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] They cover various additional issues besides the aims of education, like what topics are learned and how the learning activity is structured.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Other themes include the role of the teacher, how educational progress should be assessed, and how institutional frameworks and policies should be structured.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] There are many ideologies, and they often overlap in various ways.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Teacher-centered ideologies place the main emphasis on the teacher's role in transmitting knowledge to students, while student-centered ideologies give a more active role to the students in the process.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Process-based ideologies focus on what the processes of teaching and learning should be like and contrast with product-based ideologies, which discuss education from the perspective of the result to be achieved.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Conservative ideologies rely on traditional and well-established practices while Progressive ideologies emphasize innovation and creativity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Further categories are humanism, romanticism, essentialism, encyclopaedism, and pragmatism as well as authoritarian and democratic ideologies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Learning theories try to explain how learning happens.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Influential theories are behaviorism, cognitivism, and constructivism.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Behaviorism understands learning as a change in behavior in response to environmental stimuli.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This happens by presenting the learner with a stimulus, associating this stimulus with the desired response, and solidifying this stimulus-response pair.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Cognitivism sees learning as a change in cognitive structures and focuses on the mental processes involved in storing, retrieving, and processing information.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Constructivism holds that learning is based on the personal experience of each individual and puts more emphasis on social interactions and how they are interpreted by the learner.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] These theories have important implications for how to teach.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] For example, behaviorists tend to focus on drills, while cognitivists may advocate the use of mnemonics, and constructivists tend to employ collaborative learning strategies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Various theories suggest that learning is more efficient when it is based on personal experience.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] An additional factor is to aim at a deeper understanding by connecting new to pre-existing knowledge rather than merely memorizing a list of unrelated facts.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] An influential developmental theory of learning is proposed by psychologist Jean Piaget, who outlines four stages of learning through which children pass on their way to adulthood: the sensorimotor, the pre-operational, the concrete operational, and the formal operational stage.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] They correspond to different levels of abstraction with early stages focusing more on simple sensory and motor activities, while later stages include more complex internal representations and information processing in the form of logical reasoning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The teaching method concerns the way the content is presented by the teacher, for example, whether group work is used instead of a focus on individual learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] There are many teaching methods available and which one is most efficient in a case depends on factors like the subject matter and the learner's age and competence level.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This is reflected in the fact that modern school systems organize students by age, competence, specialization, and native language into different classes to ensure a productive learning process.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Different subjects frequently use different approaches; for instance, language education often focuses on verbal learning, while mathematical education is about abstract and symbolic thinking together with deductive reasoning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] One central requirement for teaching methodologies is to ensure that the learner remains motivated because of interest and curiosity or through external rewards.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Teaching method also encompasses the use of instructional media used, such as books, worksheets, and audio-visual recordings, and having some form of test or assessment to evaluate the learning progress.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Educational assessment is the process of documenting the student's knowledge and skills, which can happen formally or informally and may take place before, during, or after the learning activity.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] An important pedagogical aspect in many forms of modern education is that each lesson is part of a larger educational enterprise governed by a syllabus, which often covers several months or years.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] According to Herbartianism, teaching is divided into phases.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The initial phase consists of preparing the student's mind for new information.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Next, new ideas are first presented to the learner and then associated with ideas with which the learner is already familiar.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In later phases, the understanding shifts to a more general level behind the specific instances, and the ideas are then put into concrete practice.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The history of education studies the processes, methods, and institutions involved in teaching and learning.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It tries to explain how they have interacted with each other and shaped educational practice until the present day.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Education in prehistory took place as a form of enculturation and focused on practical knowledge and skills relevant to everyday concerns, for example, in relation to food, clothing, shelter, and protection.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] There were no formal schools or specialized teachers, and most adults in the community performed that role and learning happened informally during everyday activities, for example, when children observed and imitated their elders.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] For these oral societies, storytelling played a key role in transferring cultural and religious ideas from one generation to the next.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Beginning with the emergence of agriculture around 9000 BCE, a slow educational change towards more specialization began to occur as people formed larger groups and more complex artisanal and technical skills were needed.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Starting in the 4th millennium BCE and continuing through the following millennia, a major shift in educational practices started to take place with the invention of writing in regions such as Mesopotamia, ancient Egypt, the Indus Valley, and ancient China.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This development had a significant influence on the history of education as a whole.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Through writing, it was possible to store, preserve, and communicate information.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This facilitated various subsequent developments; for example, the creation of educational tools, like textbooks, and the formation of institutions, like schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Another key aspect of ancient education was the establishment of formal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This became necessary since the amount of knowledge grew as civilizations evolved, and informal education proved insufficient to transmit all requisite knowledge between generations.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Teachers would act as specialists to impart knowledge, and education became more abstract and further removed from daily life.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Formal education was still quite rare in ancient societies and was restricted to the intellectual elites.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It covered fields like reading and writing, record keeping, leadership, civic and political life, religion, and technical skills associated with specific professions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Formal education introduced a new way of teaching that gave more emphasis to discipline and drills than the earlier informal modes of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Many aspects of education in the medieval period were shaped by religious traditions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In Europe, the Catholic Church wielded a significant influence over formal education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In the Arab world, the newly founded religion of Islam spread rapidly and led to various educational developments during the Islamic Golden Age, for example, by integrating classical and religious knowledge and by establishing madrasa schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In Jewish communities, yeshivas were established as institutions dedicated to the study of religious texts and Jewish law.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In China, an expansive state educational and exam system influenced by Confucian teachings was established.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] New complex societies began to evolve in other regions, such as Africa, the Americas, Northern Europe, and Japan.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Some incorporated preexisting educational practices, while others developed new traditions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Additionally, this period saw the establishment of various institutes of higher education and research.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The first universities in Europe were the University of Bologna, the University of Paris, and Oxford University.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Other influential centers of higher learning were the Al-Qarawiyyin University in Morocco, the Al-Azhar University in Egypt, and the House of Wisdom in Iraq.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Another key development was the creation of guilds, which were associations of skilled craftsmen and merchants who controlled the practice of their trades.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] They were responsible for vocational education, and new members had to pass through different stages on their way to masterhood.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Starting in the early modern period, education in Europe during the Renaissance slowly began to shift from a religious approach towards one which was more secular.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This development was tied to an increased appreciation of the importance of education and a broadened range of topics, including a revived interest in ancient literary texts and educational programs.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The turn toward secularization was accelerated during the Age of Enlightenment starting in the 17th century, which emphasized the role of reason and the empirical sciences.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] European colonization affected education in the Americas through Christian missionary initiatives.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In China, the state educational system was further expanded and focused more on the teachings of neo-Confucianism.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In the Islamic world, the outreach of formal education increased and remained under the influence of religion.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] A key development in the early modern period was the invention and popularization of the printing press in the middle of the 15th century, which had a profound impact on general education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] It significantly reduced the cost of producing books, which were hand-written before, and thereby augmented the dissemination of written documents, including new forms like newspapers and pamphlets.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The increased availability of written media had a major influence on the general literacy of the population.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] These changes prepared the rise of public education in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This period saw the establishment of publicly funded schools with the aim of providing education for all.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This contrasts with earlier periods when formal education was primarily provided by private schools, religious institutions, and individual tutors.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Aztec civilization was an exception in this regard since formal education was mandatory for the youth regardless of social class as early as the 14th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Closely related changes were to make education compulsory and free of charge for all children up to a certain age.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Initiatives to promote public education and universal access to education made significant progress in the 20th and the 21st centuries and were promoted by intergovernmental organizations like the UN.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Examples include the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the Convention on the Rights of the Child, the Education for All initiative, the Millennium Development Goals, and the Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] These efforts resulted in a steady rise of all forms of education but affected primary education in particular.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] In 1970, 28% of all primary-school-age children worldwide did not attend school; by 2015, this number dropped to 9%.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The establishment of public education was accompanied by the introduction of standardized curricula for public schools as well as standardized tests to assess the student's progress.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Similar changes also affected teachers by setting in place institutions and norms to guide and oversee teacher training, like certification requirements for teaching at public schools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Emerging educational technologies have shaped contemporary education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] The widespread availability of computers and the internet dramatically increased access to educational resources and made new types of education possible, such as online education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] This was of particular relevance during the COVID-19 pandemic when schools globally closed for extended periods and many offered remote learning through video conferencing or pre-recorded video lessons to continue instruction.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/education-p02] Contemporary education is also shaped by the increased globalization and internationalization of education.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The traditional disciplines of engineering are civil, mechanical, electrical, and chemical.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The academic discipline of engineering encompasses a broad range of more specialized subfields, and each can have a more specific emphasis for applications of mathematics and science.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Modern engineering practice follows the engineering design process and spans multiple fields, which include designing and improving infrastructure, machinery, vehicles, electronics, materials, and energy systems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] As a human endeavor, engineering has existed since ancient times, starting with the six classic simple machines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Examples of large-scale engineering projects from antiquity include impressive structures like the pyramids, elegant temples such as the Parthenon, and water conveyances like hulled watercraft, canals, and the Roman aqueduct.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Early machines were powered by humans and animals, then later by wind.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Machines of war were invented for siegecraft.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In Europe, the scientific and industrial revolutions advanced engineering into a scientific profession and resulted in continuing technological improvements.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The steam engine provided much greater power than animals, leading to mechanical propulsion for ships and railways.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Further scientific advances resulted in the application of engineering to electrical, chemical, and aerospace requirements, plus the use of new materials for greater efficiencies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The word *engineering* is derived from the Latin *ingenium*.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers typically follow a code of ethics that favors honesty and integrity, while being dedicated to public safety and welfare.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering tasks involve finding optimal solutions to constrained problems, with testing and simulations being used prior to production.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] When a deployed product fails, forensic engineering is used to determine what went wrong in order to find a fix.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Much of this product lifecycle management is now assisted with computer software, from design to testing and manufacturing.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] At larger scales, this process is normally funded by a company, multiple investors, or the government, so a knowledge of economics and business practices is needed.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering has existed since ancient times, when humans devised inventions such as the wedge, lever, wheel and pulley, etc.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The term *engineering* is derived from the word *engineer*, which itself dates back to the 14th century when an *engine'er* (literally, one who builds or operates a *siege engine*) referred to "a constructor of military engines".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In this context, now obsolete, an "engine" referred to a military machine, *i.e.*, a mechanical contraption used in war (for example, a catapult).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Notable examples of the obsolete usage which have survived to the present day are military engineering corps, *e.g.*, the U.S.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The word "engine" itself is of even older origin, ultimately deriving from the Latin *ingenium* (c.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Other monuments, no longer standing, such as the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the Pharos of Alexandria, were important engineering achievements of their time and were considered among the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The six classic simple machines were known in the ancient Near East.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The wedge and the inclined plane (ramp) were known since prehistoric times.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The wheel, along with the wheel and axle mechanism, was invented in Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) during the 5th millennium BC.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The lever mechanism first appeared around 5,000 years ago in the Near East, where it was used in a simple balance scale, and to move large objects in Egyptian technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The lever was also used in the shadoof water-lifting device, the first crane machine, which appeared in Mesopotamia c.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] 3000 BC, and then in Egyptian technology c.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest evidence of pulleys date back to Mesopotamia in the early 2nd millennium BC, and ancient Egypt during the Twelfth Dynasty (1991–1802 BC).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The screw, the last of the simple machines to be invented, first appeared in Mesopotamia during the Neo-Assyrian period (911–609) BC.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The Egyptian pyramids were built using three of the six simple machines, the inclined plane, the wedge, and the lever, to create structures like the Great Pyramid of Giza.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest civil engineer known by name is Imhotep.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] As one of the officials of the Pharaoh, Djosèr, he probably designed and supervised the construction of the Pyramid of Djoser (the Step Pyramid) at Saqqara in Egypt around 2630–2611 BC.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest practical water-powered machines, the water wheel and watermill, first appeared in the Persian Empire, in what are now Iraq and Iran, by the early 4th century BC.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Kush developed the Sakia during the 4th century BC, which relied on animal power instead of human energy.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Hafirs were developed as a type of reservoir in Kush to store and contain water as well as boost irrigation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Kushite ancestors built speos during the Bronze Age between 3700 and 3250 BC.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Bloomeries and blast furnaces were also created during the 7th centuries BC in Kush.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Wooden plank-built seafaring ships were being engineered and built during the Bronze Age, as evidenced by the Uluburun shipwreck, dated from around 1300 BCE.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Ancient Greece developed machines in both civilian and military domains, as evidenced by the writings of Philo of Byzantium and others.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The Antikythera mechanism, an early known mechanical analog computer, and the mechanical inventions of Archimedes, are examples of Greek mechanical engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Ancient Chinese, Greek, Roman and Hunnic armies employed military machines and inventions such as artillery which was developed by the Greeks around the 4th century BC, the trireme, the ballista and the catapult, the trebuchet by Chinese circa 6th-5th century BCE.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest practical wind-powered machines, the windmill and wind pump, first appeared in the Muslim world during the Islamic Golden Age, in what are now Iran, Afghanistan, and Pakistan, by the 9th century AD.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest practical steam-powered machine was a steam jack driven by a steam turbine, described in 1551 by Taqi al-Din Muhammad ibn Ma'ruf in Ottoman Egypt.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The cotton gin was invented in India by the 6th century AD, and the spinning wheel was invented in the Islamic world by the early 11th century, both of which were fundamental to the growth of the cotton industry.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The spinning wheel was also a precursor to the spinning jenny, which was a key development during the early Industrial Revolution in the 18th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The earliest programmable machines were developed in the Muslim world.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] A music sequencer, a programmable musical instrument, was the earliest type of programmable machine.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The first music sequencer was an automated flute player invented by the Banu Musa brothers, described in their *Book of Ingenious Devices*, in the 9th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In 1206, Al-Jazari invented programmable automata/robots.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] He described four automaton musicians, including drummers operated by a programmable drum machine, where they could be made to play different rhythms and different drum patterns.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Before the development of modern engineering, mathematics was used by artisans and craftsmen, such as millwrights, clockmakers, instrument makers and surveyors.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Aside from these professions, universities were not believed to have had much practical significance to technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] A standard reference for the state of mechanical arts during the Renaissance is given in the mining engineering treatise *De re metallica* (1556), which also contains sections on geology, mining, and chemistry.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] *De re metallica* was the standard chemistry reference for the next 180 years.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The science of classical mechanics, sometimes called Newtonian mechanics, formed the scientific basis of much of modern engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] With the rise of engineering as a profession in the 18th century, the term became more narrowly applied to fields in which mathematics and science were applied to these ends.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Similarly, in addition to military and civil engineering, the fields then known as the mechanic arts became incorporated into engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Canal building was an important engineering work during the early phases of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] John Smeaton was the first self-proclaimed civil engineer and is often regarded as the "father" of civil engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] He was an English civil engineer responsible for the design of bridges, canals, harbors, and lighthouses.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] He was also a capable mechanical engineer and an eminent physicist.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Using a model water wheel, Smeaton conducted experiments for seven years, determining ways to increase efficiency.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Smeaton introduced iron axles and gears to water wheels.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Smeaton also made mechanical improvements to the Newcomen steam engine.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Smeaton designed the third Eddystone Lighthouse (1755–59) where he pioneered the use of 'hydraulic lime' (a form of mortar which will set under water) and developed a technique involving dovetailed blocks of granite in the building of the lighthouse.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] He is important in the history, rediscovery of, and development of modern cement, because he identified the compositional requirements needed to obtain "hydraulicity" in lime; work which led ultimately to the invention of Portland cement.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Applied science led to the development of the steam engine.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Edward Somerset, 2nd Marquess of Worcester published a book of 100 inventions containing a method for raising waters similar to a coffee percolator.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Samuel Morland, a mathematician and inventor who worked on pumps, left notes at the Vauxhall Ordinance Office on a steam pump design that Thomas Savery read.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In 1698 Savery built a steam pump called "The Miner's Friend".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Iron merchant Thomas Newcomen, who built the first commercial piston steam engine in 1712, was not known to have any scientific training.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The application of steam-powered cast iron blowing cylinders for providing pressurized air for blast furnaces lead to a large increase in iron production in the late 18th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The higher furnace temperatures made possible with steam-powered blast allowed for the use of more lime in blast furnaces, which enabled the transition from charcoal to coke.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These innovations lowered the cost of iron, making horse railways and iron bridges practical.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The puddling process, patented by Henry Cort in 1784 produced large scale quantities of wrought iron.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Hot blast, patented by James Beaumont Neilson in 1828, greatly lowered the amount of fuel needed to smelt iron.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] With the development of the high pressure steam engine, the power to weight ratio of steam engines made practical steamboats and locomotives possible.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] New steel making processes, such as the Bessemer process and the open hearth furnace, ushered in an area of heavy engineering in the late 19th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] One of the most famous engineers of the mid-19th century was Isambard Kingdom Brunel, who built railroads, dockyards and steamships.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The Industrial Revolution created a demand for machinery with metal parts, which led to the development of several machine tools.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Boring cast iron cylinders with precision was not possible until John Wilkinson invented his boring machine, which is considered the first machine tool.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Other machine tools included the screw cutting lathe, milling machine, turret lathe and the metal planer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Precision machining techniques were developed in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These included the use of gigs to guide the machining tool over the work and fixtures to hold the work in the proper position.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Machine tools and machining techniques capable of producing interchangeable parts lead to large scale factory production by the late 19th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The United States Census of 1850 listed the occupation of "engineer" for the first time with a count of 2,000.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There were fewer than 50 engineering graduates in the U.S. before 1865.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The first PhD in engineering (technically, *applied science and engineering*) awarded in the United States went to Josiah Willard Gibbs at Yale University in 1863; it was also the second PhD awarded in science in the U.S.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In 1870 there were a dozen U.S. mechanical engineering graduates, with that number increasing to 43 per year in 1875.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In 1890, there were 6,000 engineers in civil, mining, mechanical and electrical.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There was no chair of applied mechanism and applied mechanics at Cambridge until 1875, and no chair of engineering at Oxford until 1907.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Germany established technical universities earlier.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The foundations of electrical engineering in the 1800s included the experiments of Alessandro Volta, Michael Faraday, Georg Ohm and others and the invention of the electric telegraph in 1816 and the electric motor in 1872.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The theoretical work of James Maxwell (see: Maxwell's equations) and Heinrich Hertz in the late 19th century gave rise to the field of electronics.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The later inventions of the vacuum tube and the transistor further accelerated the development of electronics to such an extent that electrical and electronics engineers currently outnumber their colleagues of any other engineering specialty.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Chemical engineering developed in the late nineteenth century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Industrial scale manufacturing demanded new materials and new processes and by 1880 the need for large scale production of chemicals was such that a new industry was created, dedicated to the development and large scale manufacturing of chemicals in new industrial plants.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The role of the chemical engineer was the design of these chemical plants and processes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Originally deriving from the manufacture of ceramics and its putative derivative metallurgy, materials science is one of the oldest forms of engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Modern materials science evolved directly from metallurgy, which itself evolved from the use of fire.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Important elements of modern materials science were products of the Space Race; the understanding and engineering of the metallic alloys, and silica and carbon materials, used in building space vehicles enabling the exploration of space.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Materials science has driven, and been driven by, the development of revolutionary technologies such as rubbers, plastics, semiconductors, and biomaterials.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Aeronautical engineering deals with aircraft design process design while aerospace engineering is a more modern term that expands the reach of the discipline by including spacecraft design.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Its origins can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the start of the 20th century although the work of Sir George Cayley has recently been dated as being from the last decade of the 18th century.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Only a decade after the successful flights by the Wright brothers, there was extensive development of aeronautical engineering through development of military aircraft that were used in World War I.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Meanwhile, research to provide fundamental background science continued by combining theoretical physics with experiments.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering is a broad discipline that is often broken down into several sub-disciplines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Although most engineers will usually be trained in a specific discipline, some engineers become multi-disciplined through experience.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Below is a list of recognized branches of engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Note that there are additional sub-disciplines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Interdisciplinary engineering draws from more than one of the principle branches of the practice.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Historically, naval engineering and mining engineering were major branches.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Other engineering fields are manufacturing engineering, acoustical engineering, corrosion engineering, instrumentation and control, automotive, information engineering, petroleum, systems, audio, software, architectural, biosystems, and textile engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These and other branches of engineering are represented in the 40 licensed member institutions of the UK Engineering Council, as of 2025.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] New specialties sometimes combine with the traditional fields and form new branches – for example, Earth systems engineering and management involves a wide range of subject areas including engineering studies, environmental science, engineering ethics and philosophy of engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] One who practices engineering is called an engineer, and those licensed to do so may have more formal designations such as Professional Engineer, Chartered Engineer, Incorporated Engineer, Ingenieur, European Engineer.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There can also be what is called by the FAA a Designated Engineering Representative.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In the engineering design process, engineers apply mathematics and the physical sciences to find novel solutions to problems or to improve existing solutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers need proficient knowledge of relevant sciences for their design projects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] As a result, many engineers continue to learn new material throughout their careers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] If multiple solutions exist, engineers weigh each design choice based on their merit and choose the solution that best matches the requirements.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The task of the engineer is to identify, understand, and interpret the constraints on a design in order to yield a successful result.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] It is generally insufficient to build a technically successful product, rather, it must also meet further requirements.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Constraints may include the fundamental laws of physics and chemistry, available resources, physical, imaginative or technical limitations, flexibility for future modifications and additions, and other factors, such as requirements for cost, safety, marketability, productivity, and serviceability.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] By understanding the constraints, engineers derive specifications for the limits within which a viable object or system may be produced and operated.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers use their knowledge of science, mathematics, logic, economics, and appropriate experience or tacit knowledge to find suitable solutions to a particular problem.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Creating an appropriate mathematical model of a problem often allows them to analyze it (sometimes definitively), and to test potential solutions.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] More than one solution to a design problem usually exists so the different design choices have to be evaluated on their merits before the one judged most suitable is chosen.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Genrich Altshuller, after gathering statistics on a large number of patents, suggested that compromises are at the heart of "low-level" engineering designs, while at a higher level the best design is one which eliminates the core contradiction causing the problem.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers typically attempt to predict how well their designs will perform to their specifications prior to full-scale production.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] They use, among other things: prototypes, scale models, simulations, destructive tests, nondestructive tests, and stress tests.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Testing ensures that products will perform as expected but only in so far as the testing has been representative of use in service.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] For products, such as aircraft, that are used differently by different users failures and unexpected shortcomings (and necessary design changes) can be expected throughout the operational life of the product.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers take on the responsibility of producing designs that will perform as well as expected and, except those employed in specific areas of the arms industry, will not harm people.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers typically include a factor of safety in their designs to reduce the risk of unexpected failure.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] This philosophy is embodied by Cicero's Creed, now considered the original engineer's code of ethics.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The study of failed products is known as forensic engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] It attempts to identify the cause of failure to allow a redesign of the product and so prevent a re-occurrence.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Careful analysis is needed to establish the cause of failure of a product.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The consequences of a failure may vary in severity from the minor cost of a machine breakdown to large loss of life in the case of accidents involving aircraft and large stationary structures like buildings and dams.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These larger scale engineering disasters can arise from shortcuts or errors in the design process, such as miscalculations and miscommunication.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] They can also happen as a result of fatigue failure due to stress, temperature, or corrosion.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Faulty computer software can also play a role.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] As with all modern scientific and technological endeavors, computers and software play an increasingly important role.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] As well as the typical business application software there are a number of computer aided applications (computer-aided technologies) specifically for engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Computers can be used to generate models of fundamental physical processes, which can be solved using numerical methods.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] One of the most widely used design tools in the profession is computer-aided design (CAD) software.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] It enables engineers to create 3D models, 2D drawings, and schematics of their designs.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] CAD together with digital mockup (DMU) and CAE software such as finite element method analysis or analytic element method allows engineers to create models of designs that can be analyzed without having to make expensive and time-consuming physical prototypes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Access and distribution of all this information is generally organized with the use of product data management software.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In recent years the use of computer software to aid the development of goods has collectively come to be known as product lifecycle management (PLM).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The engineering profession engages in a range of activities, from collaboration at the societal level, and smaller individual projects.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Almost all engineering projects are obligated to a funding source: a company, a set of investors, or a government.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The types of engineering that are less constrained by such a funding source, are *pro bono*, and open-design engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering has interconnections with society, culture, and human behavior.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Most products and constructions used by modern society, are influenced by engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering activities have an impact on the environment, society, economies, and public safety.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering projects can be controversial.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Examples from different engineering disciplines include: the development of nuclear weapons, the Three Gorges Dam, the design and use of sport utility vehicles, and the extraction of oil.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In response, some engineering companies have enacted serious corporate and social responsibility policies.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The attainment of many of the Millennium Development Goals requires the achievement of sufficient engineering capacity to develop infrastructure and sustainable technological development.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Overseas development and relief NGOs make considerable use of engineers, to apply solutions in disaster and development scenarios.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering companies in more developed economies face challenges with regard to the number of engineers being trained, compared with those retiring.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] This problem is prominent in the UK where engineering has a poor image and low status.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There are negative economic and political issues that this can cause, as well as ethical issues.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] It is agreed the engineering profession faces an "image crisis".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The UK holds the most engineering companies compared to other European countries, together with the United States.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Many engineering societies have established codes of practice and codes of ethics to guide members and inform the public at large.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In Canada, engineers wear the Iron Ring as a symbol and reminder of the obligations and ethics associated with their profession.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There exists an overlap between the sciences and engineering practice; in engineering, one applies science.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Both areas of endeavor rely on accurate observation of materials and phenomena.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Both use mathematics and classification criteria to analyze and communicate observations.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Scientists may also have to complete engineering tasks, such as designing experimental apparatus or building prototypes.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Conversely, in the process of developing technology, engineers sometimes find themselves exploring new phenomena, thus becoming, for the moment, scientists or more precisely "engineering scientists".
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In the book *What Engineers Know and How They Know It*, Walter Vincenti asserts that engineering research has a character different from that of scientific research.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] First, it often deals with areas in which the basic physics or chemistry are well understood, but the problems themselves are too complex to solve in an exact manner.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There is a "real and important" difference between engineering and physics as similar to any science field has to do with technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Physics is an exploratory science that seeks knowledge of principles while engineering uses knowledge for practical applications of principles.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The former equates an understanding into a mathematical principle while the latter measures variables involved and creates technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] For technology, physics is an auxiliary and in a way technology is considered as applied physics.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Though physics and engineering are interrelated, it does not mean that a physicist is trained to do an engineer's job.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] A physicist would typically require additional and relevant training.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Physicists and engineers engage in different lines of work.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] But PhD physicists who specialize in sectors of engineering physics and applied physics are titled as Technology officer, R&D Engineers and System Engineers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] An example of this is the use of numerical approximations to the Navier–Stokes equations to describe aerodynamic flow over an aircraft, or the use of the finite element method to calculate the stresses in complex components.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Second, engineering research employs many semi-empirical methods that are foreign to pure scientific research, one example being the method of parameter variation.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The study of the human body, albeit from different directions and for different purposes, is an important common link between medicine and some engineering disciplines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Medicine aims to sustain, repair, enhance and even replace functions of the human body, if necessary, through the use of technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Modern medicine can replace several of the body's functions through the use of artificial organs and can significantly alter the function of the human body through artificial devices such as, for example, brain implants and pacemakers.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The fields of bionics and medical bionics are dedicated to the study of synthetic implants pertaining to natural systems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Conversely, some engineering disciplines view the human body as a biological machine worth studying and are dedicated to emulating many of its functions by replacing biology with technology.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] This has led to fields such as artificial intelligence, neural networks, fuzzy logic, and robotics.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There are also substantial interdisciplinary interactions between engineering and medicine.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Both fields provide solutions to real world problems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] This often requires moving forward before phenomena are completely understood in a more rigorous scientific sense and therefore experimentation and empirical knowledge is an integral part of both.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Medicine, in part, studies the function of the human body.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The human body, as a biological machine, has many functions that can be modeled using engineering methods.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The heart for example functions much like a pump, the skeleton is like a linked structure with levers, the brain produces electrical signals etc.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These similarities as well as the increasing importance and application of engineering principles in medicine, led to the development of the field of biomedical engineering that uses concepts developed in both disciplines.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Newly emerging branches of science, such as systems biology, are adapting analytical tools traditionally used for engineering, such as systems modeling and computational analysis, to the description of biological systems.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] There are connections between engineering and art, for example, architecture, landscape architecture and industrial design (even to the extent that these disciplines may sometimes be included in a university's Faculty of Engineering).
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The Art Institute of Chicago, for instance, held an exhibition about the art of NASA's aerospace design.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Robert Maillart's bridge design is perceived by some to have been deliberately artistic.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] At the University of South Florida, an engineering professor, through a grant with the National Science Foundation, has developed a course that connects art and engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Among famous historical figures, Leonardo da Vinci is a well-known Renaissance artist and engineer, and a prime example of the nexus between art and engineering.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Business engineering deals with the relationship between professional engineering, IT systems, business administration and change management.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineering management or "Management engineering" is a specialized field of management concerned with engineering practice or the engineering industry sector.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] The demand for management-focused engineers (or from the opposite perspective, managers with an understanding of engineering), has resulted in the development of specialized engineering management degrees that develop the knowledge and skills needed for these roles.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] During an engineering management course, students will develop industrial engineering skills, knowledge, and expertise, alongside knowledge of business administration, management techniques, and strategic thinking.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Engineers specializing in change management must have in-depth knowledge of the application of industrial and organizational psychology principles and methods.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Professional engineers often train as certified management consultants in the very specialized field of management consulting applied to engineering practice or the engineering sector.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] This combination of technical engineering practice, management consulting practice, industry sector knowledge, and change management expertise enables professional engineers who are also qualified as management consultants to lead major business transformation initiatives.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] These initiatives are typically sponsored by C-level executives.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] In political science, the term *engineering* has been borrowed for the study of the subjects of social engineering and political engineering, which deal with forming political and social structures using engineering methodology coupled with political science principles.
[src:american-society-for-engineering-education/engineering] Marketing engineering and financial engineering have similarly borrowed the term.
